      "anchor_proposed": {
        "vr_id": 1729,
        "reference": "2Pe 3:9",
        "strongs": "G1014",
        "translit": "boulomai",
        "anchor_rationale": "'The Lord is not slow to fulfill his promise...not wishing that any should perish, but that all should reach repentance.' God's purposive will directed universally toward repentance and life is stated here in its most expansive form. The verb carries its full theological weight: the divine boulomai is an inner volitional act that defines what God actively desires and purposes toward the world."
      }
    },
    {
      "code": "M15-E-VCG02",
      "label": "Considered inner resolution and authoritative judgment (gnōmē)",
      "context_description": "The term names the inner considered resolution — Paul's deliberate judgment offered without a dominical command, the collective resolution that unites or divides a community, the unified purpose God places in the hearts of the hostile kings. The phenomenon is a formed inner judgment held as a resolution rather than an impulse. Inner-being phenomenon: considered inner resolution.",
